flowRoot.flowPara: Porting Mozilla Open Badges onto XO laptops through Lemonade Stand
Open Badges are an open-source attempt at recognizing education in a digital age.
Open Badges can be created and issued by anyone to recognize one's skills and accomplishments.
Each badge has a name, pupose, and criteria for being awarded to allow for quick identification of achievements completed outside of the classroom.
XO Laptops were created by the Nicholas Negroponte and Walter Bender in the MIT Media lab in an attempt to create a $100 laptop in 2007.
Backed by the UN, today over 2.5 million laptops have been ordered and shipped all over the world.
Tbe XO Laptops were built from the ground up for children to learn and embrace technology.

The original UI of the game was difficult for kids to get used to, and the original store menu only had bulk items which were complicated to calculate. The recipe of the Lemonade couldn't be changed and one would unrealistically sell all of their lemonade that the weather permitted. The game was also limited to Lemonade and English, which aren't the most international concepts for children to get used to.
Lastly, we created an activity called Sash for the XO laptops which could display the badges and achievments acquired during gameplay.
The badges are locally stored and are awarded once a set of conditions are met.
Though originally implemented for Lemonade Stand, the Sash activity reads from the XO's datastore and can award badges for any XO software.

We started by analyzing an educational game for the XO Laptops created by RIT students a couple of years ago. This game, Lemonade Stand, was designed to show and teach children the basic business, microeconomic, and math skills involved in running a Lemonade Stand.
After testing it a bit ourselves, we brought it to a local middleschool for the youth to playtest it as well on National Lemonade day.
